    "body": "### Problem\n\n- Following up on the discussion on #27489\n\n### Problem\n\n`exrc` works well when Neovim is started from the project directory, but users who start Neovim from `$HOME` and navigate to different projects from within the editor get no equivalent benefit. The only tool available for this workflow is `vim.secure.read()`, which handles trust verification but stops there — it returns the file contents as a string and leaves execution entirely to the caller.\n\nSourcing a trusted `.nvim.lua` correctly requires trivial, but mandatory boilerplate:\n\n```lua\nlocal content = vim.secure.read(path)\nif content == nil then return end\n\nlocal chunk, err = load(content, \"@\" .. path)\nif not chunk then\n  vim.notify(err, vim.log.levels.ERROR)\n  return\nend\n\nlocal ok, run_err = pcall(chunk)\nif not ok then\n  vim.notify(run_err, vim.log.levels.ERROR)\nend\n```\n\nEvery user who wants this pattern must independently rediscover and reimplement it. The API exposes a low-level primitive where a high-level one is almost always what's needed.\n\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n\n### Proposal\n\nAdd `vim.secure.source(path)` — a thin wrapper that calls `vim.secure.read()` internally, then compiles and executes the result if trusted. Semantically equivalent to `vim.secure.read()` + `load()` + `pcall()`, with proper error reporting and chunk naming.\n\nThis would let users (or plugin authors) handle the `DirChanged` use case cleanly:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"DirChanged\", {\n  callback = function()\n    vim.secure.source(vim.fn.getcwd() .. \"/.nvim.lua\")\n  end,\n})\n```\n\n`vim.secure.read()` would remain unchanged for callers who need the raw content. `vim.secure.source()` is purely additive.",
